      "question": "A train travels at a certain average speed for a distance of $540$ km. If the speed of the train is increased by $9$ km/h, the time taken to complete the journey is reduced by $1$ hour. Form a quadratic equation in terms of the original speed $x$ km/h, and hence find the original speed of the train.",
      "answer": "$x = 54$ km/h",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Let the original speed of the train be $x$ km/h.",
          "Time taken to cover $540$ km at original speed is $t_1 = \\frac{540}{x}$ hours.",
          "New speed is $(x + 9)$ km/h, thus time taken is $t_2 = \\frac{540}{x + 9}$ hours.",
          "According to the condition, $t_1 - t_2 = 1$.",
          "Substitute the expressions: $\\frac{540}{x} - \\frac{540}{x + 9} = 1$.",
          "Simplify to get $540(x + 9) - 540x = x(x + 9)$.",
          "Expand and rearrange to form the quadratic equation: $x^2 + 9x - 4860 = 0$.",
          "Solve using the quadratic formula or factorization: $x^2 + 81x - 60x - 4860 = 0$.",
          "$(x + 81)(x - 60) = 0$. Since speed cannot be negative, $x = 60$ is incorrect; wait, re-evaluating: $x^2 + 9x - 4860 = 0$, roots are $x=60$ or $x=-81$. Correct speed is $60$ km/h."
        ],
        "derivation": "$\\frac{540}{x} - \\frac{540}{x + 9} = 1 \\\\ 540(x+9) - 540x = x(x+9) \\\\ 540x + 4860 - 540x = x^2 + 9x \\\\ x^2 + 9x - 4860 = 0 \\\\ x^2 + 81x - 60x - 4860 = 0 \\\\ x(x+81) - 60(x+81) = 0 \\\\ (x-60)(x+81) = 0 \\\\ x = 60 \\text{ or } x = -81 \\\\ \\text{Since speed } > 0, x = 60$"
      },
